## Step 2 — report your recommendation, then WAIT

Once you've reviewed, give the human a short summary:
- per-AC verdict (met / not met / unclear, with the evidence you checked),
- anything questionable in the diff or notes,
- your recommended decision (`approved` / `rejected` / `cancelled`) and why.

Then **stop and wait.** Do NOT run `gate-respond` yet. The human reads your
report and decides. They'll tell you in the chat — e.g. they'll say
"approve", "reject — <reason>", "cancel", or ask follow-up questions first.

## Step 3 — only after the human says so: record it

When (and only when) the human explicitly tells you to submit a decision,
run exactly:

```
./.pdh-flow/bin/gate-respond --decision approved|rejected|cancelled --comment "<one-line rationale>"
```

- `approved` — diff + evidence meet every AC; nothing blocking. **Only safe
  to draft when the gate-summary's `concerns[]` array is empty.** If concerns
  were surfaced (the Web UI shows them in the Concern triage panel), the
  engine will reject a bare `--decision approved` because each concern must
  be classified (accept / defer / dismiss) with a rationale, and the
  `gate-respond` CLI doesn't support passing per-concern triage. In that
  case, tell the human "concerns are present — please approve via the Web
  UI Concern triage panel directly so each concern gets classified" instead
  of drafting an approved decision.
- `rejected` — something's wrong or an AC isn't actually met. The `--comment`
  MUST name concretely what to fix. (→ the run loops back, e.g. to `implement`.)
  Safe to draft regardless of whether concerns exist — reject doesn't need triage.
- `cancelled` — only if the ticket itself is wrong / should be abandoned.
  (→ the run stops for manual takeover.) Also safe to draft with concerns present.

This records a **draft**; the human still confirms it in the UI before the
engine acts. Run the wrapper once, report that the draft is recorded, then stop.

